Here is some code. Most of it is from the Microsoft help file:


#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <time.h>

void main( void )
{
   int i;
   int random1or2
   /* Seed the random-number generator with current time so that
    * the numbers will be different every time we run.
    */
   srand( (unsigned)time( NULL ) );

   /* Display 10 numbers. */
   for( i = 0;   i < 1000; i++ )
   {
      random1or2 = (rand() % 2) + 1;
      printf( "%d&#92;n", random1or2);
   }
   return;
}

So this is pretty straightforward. I'm assuing you are using C++ since if this is C you need a typedef or struct Node * instead of Node *. It would be helpful if you'd indicate if the code compiles and doesn't work, or if it doesn't even compile.

You never make good on this comment:
//if list is empty, return 0

Seems like you ought to say something like:
 if (!head) { head=new Node; head->value=val; head->next=NULL; return; } 


Here you walk to the position you want to insert into. Of course, if the list isn't this long, you get a null pointer reference:
while(i < (pos-1) ){
temp=temp->next;
i++;
}

If you want to stick with your original comment I'd say if (temp->next==NULL) return;

// So this makes a circular reference! When done
newnode points to temp, but temp points to newnode

That's not good! You need to insert differently. If you really want to insert before, you need to remember the previous next pointer so that you can "patch" the linked list. 

newNode= new Node;
newNode->next = temp->next;
newNode->value=val;
temp->next=newNode;
}
//end list_insert()

Myspace customizations generally work off CSS. When you go to edit your profile, you add in extra code to one of the boxes; generally, in the "About Me" section. Add in the following:

<style type='text/css'>
/* CSS CODE GOES HERE */
</style>

Replace the "/* CSS CODE GOES HERE */" with whatever CSS statements you want, and you're good to go. For my page, I tried out the following, which makes everything red:

* {background:rgb(255,64,0); border:none;}
.orangetext15 {color:rgb(255,64,0);}


There are also websites out there specifically for this purpose. Search for "customize myspace", "myspace editor", etc. These will give you the proper CSS code for what you want.

They do nominate candidates. The Libertarian and Green Parties both nominate the candidates. However, only the major parties the Democrats and Republicans. In particular, there are different requirements for listing in each state.

There are other factors working against minor parties, namely:

* the use of a first past the post system advantages large parties;

* American parties are much more diverse than in other countries as there is little party cohesion - for example, many southern Democrats have traditionally been much less liberal than the party as a whole.

Minor party candidates are at a major disadvantage in resources and in gaining media attention as the media focus on the candidates who are likely to be elected.

In the 2004 Presidential election, there were 6 candidates for President outside Bush and Kerry including:

* Ralph Nader, Independent and Reform, 463,563;

* Michael Badnarik Libertarian 397,265;

